h: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stourton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from any of three places named Stourton (Staffs, Wilts, Warwicks).","2  English:  see  Sturton  .","3  English: locative name, perhaps occasionally from Storrington (Sussex), which is recorded as  <i>Storgetune</i> in 1086."],"variants":[{"name":"Storton","meanings":["English:  see  Stourton  ."]},{"name":"Sturton","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Sturton le Steeple (Notts), Great Sturton (Lincs), Sturton by Stow (Lincs), or possibly Sturton (Northumb), all of which place-names share the same etymology and early spellings as   Stratton  .","2  English:  see  Stourton  ."]}]},{"name":"Eudes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Eade  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Eads","meanings":["and Norwegian equivalent of <b>Matthew</b> ."]},{"name":"Eade","meanings":["Transferred use of the surname, which originated as a nickname from a word denoting something round and lumpish. It is one of several given names that owe their origin to their use for a character in  Margaret Mitchell's  novel Gone with the Wind (  1936 )."]},{"name":"Edes","meanings":["This name is found as a variant or pet form of   Edith   in Yorkshire from the 15th century onwards. It is recorded as a baptismal name in the 16th century. In present-day use it probably refers to the biblical ‘Garden of Eden’, crew ῾<i>eden</i> ‘place of pleasure’. As a boy's name it may also represent a variant of   Aidan   or a transferred use of a surname, itself derived in the Middle Ages from a given name <i>Edun</i> or <i>Edon</i>. This is of Old English origin, from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’."]},{"name":"Edds","meanings":["Pet form of any of several old German names beginning with <i>Ed-</i>. The Elder and Younger <i>Eddas</i> are also the names of two influential Old Icelandic books of Norse myths and poems."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Eudes de Stourton was born about 1220, in Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Michael de Stourton, was 37 and his mother, Mary Malville de Mauduit, was 32. He married Grace Hungerford in 1251, in Willey, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1285, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 67, and was buried in Stourton, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1220–Abt 1285":"umbes 1220–umbes 1285","1205–1245":"1205–1245","1218–Male":"1218–Surnud","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1225–1261":"1225–1261","1251–1303":"1251–1303","1185–1243":"1185–1243","1190–1249":"1190–1249","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1261":"1261","Abt 1285":"umbes 1285","1249":"1249","Abt 1251":"umbes 1251","1205":"1205","1303":"1303","1225":"1225","1245":"1245","Abt 1220":"umbes 1220","1243":"1243","about 1220":"umbes 1220","1218":"1218","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stourton, Wiltshire, England":"Stourton, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Stourton, Mere, Wiltshire, England":"Stourton, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Willey, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Willey, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1220–Abt 1285":"noin 1220–noin 1285","1205–1245":"1205–1245","1218–Male":"1218–Kuollut","1220–1285":"1220–1285","1225–1261":"1225–1261","1251–1303":"1251–1303","1185–1243":"1185–1243","1190–1249":"1190–1249","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1285":"1285","1251":"1251","1185":"1185","1261":"1261","Abt 1285":"noin 1285","